 Let x be the probability that a man has all three risk factors. We have


\begin{align*}p = 3 &\cdot (0.1 + x) + 0.14,\end{align*}
as we have three types of men that have 3 risk factors (A and B, B and C, A and C worded in alternative ways, 3 cases), and another 14% of men have to know exactly two of the risk factors as stated. So we already have $p$ in terms of $x$. However, we also have another equation involving $x$. Note that all the events A, B, C are mutually exclusive and inclusive of each other. Thus from the totality law we have
\begin{align*}1 &= 0 + (0.1 + x) + (0.1 + x) + (0.1 + x) + (0.14 - 2x) + (0.14 - 2x) + (0.14 - 2x) + (0.14 - 2x) + 0.1 + 0.1 + 0.1 \\ 1 &= 2.9 + 12x \\ 1 - 2.9 &= 2.2x \Rightarrow x = \frac{1}{22} \\ \Rightarrow p &= 3\left(0.1 + \frac{1}{22}\right) + 0.14 \\ &= 3\left(\frac{3}{11}\right) + \frac{7}{50} \\ &= \frac{9}{11} + \frac{7}{50} \\ &= \frac{450}{550} + \frac{77}{550} \\ &= \frac{527}{550}\end{align*}
So the answer is $\boxed{527 + 550 = \boxed{1077}}$ .

